metadata.name: Acequia #340
metadata.description:
Acequia (â€œah-seh-kee-uhâ€) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sÄqiya, meaning â€œwater carrierâ€. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

â€¨Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions. â€¨â€¨
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Matter Waves #16
metadata.description:
If light, which is generally a wave, can also sometimes be a particle - then can matter also be a wave? Louis De Broglie suggested this idea, which is supported by performing a double slit experiment with matter particles and producing an interference pattern that indicates wave behaviour. Performing the experiment with one particle at a time also produces an interference pattern, implying the particles create interference with themselves. One way this could be possible is if the particle travels infinite potential paths simultaneously, super positioning itself in many places at once. If one electron can be in infinite places at once, is it possible that all electrons are that same one? More than thinking everything is connected, can we go one further and think that everything is the same thing? 

'Matter Waves' super positions connections between constellated nodes, spreading them out through space in multiple ways - an aesthetic exploration of these ideas. 

's' to save large file
'1' to watch it load slowly 
'2' to watch it load super slowly

Fully live code in p5js

metadata.name: Polar Grid #621
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbVÃ©lo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every Ï€ Ã— 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

â€” RaphaÃ«l de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

RaphaÃ«l de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #24
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to â€œlush, greenâ€ and Brut means â€œdry, raw, or unrefined.â€

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growthâ€¦ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÌˆm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
â€˜Sâ€™ : save as png (2376â€ŠÃ—â€Š3360)
â€™Vâ€™ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
â€˜g=nâ€™ : no grain
â€˜g=pâ€™ : paper grain
â€˜h=tâ€™ : high resolution mode, 5940â€ŠÃ—â€Š8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append â€œ&g=p&h=tâ€ to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: what's left of what's left #12
metadata.description:
"The images is not a closed field of knowledge; it is a whirling, centrifugal field. It is not a fiedl of knowledge like any other; it is a movement demanding all the anthropogical aspects of being and time" Didi-Huberman

Continuing in the experimentation of photography and generative art.

What's left of what's left ... Seeks to take the reflection beyond the simple superimposition of images, highlighting the "human" x "machine" interaction.

The areas of light, fog and shadows present us with image clippings in a large tangle of visual reflections.

The algorithm builds unique images from the combination of different layers, according to a bank of photographs extracted from my own collection. In total, there are six layers containing 10 photographs each, in addition to a base layer containing 20 photos of urban fragments.

In addition, the code implements, in a random and semi-autonomous way, some adaptations such as masking, colorization, rotation and blending modes for specific layers.

* Features
Place - Where have i been. 20 distinct urban fragments;
Mode - â€œColorâ€ 80% or â€œB&Wâ€ 20%;
Zone - â€œAmazonâ€ 25%; â€œMistâ€ and â€œTerracottaâ€ 20%, â€œOld Skyâ€ 15%; and â€œOcherâ€ and â€œGoldenâ€ 10%.
Invert - 2.5%

"In a sense of overlapping past/future, not as an idea of â€‹â€‹current time, but as places of memory dispute. This "non-place", traversed by layers, is solidified in the images, almost like a truce from the endless war of this inconstancy.
there is no winner" Raffa Gomes

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

august 21, 2022

metadata.name: Natt #5
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press â€œspaceâ€ to pause the animation and â€œsâ€ to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add â€œ?pd=xâ€ (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press â€œsâ€ to save. Note, for higher values of â€œxâ€ rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size. 


Generative artwork by Tengil, 2022.

metadata.name: Snell's Artifacts #42
metadata.description:
Snell's artifacts are imaginary geometric objects created using Snell's and Descartes' laws of optics that define the behavior of a ray of light passing from one transparent medium to another.

By applying these laws to extreme parameters, beyond what the real world is capable of producing and with a high level of variability, we open the door to a new world.

In order to keep some control over this extreme and crazy world, the grid within which the rays evolve is divided into several squares. Each of these squares limits the grid settings at that location.

In order to be able to generate a Snell Artifact, 1 to 6 million rays are created. It may take a while. So be patient while these radii are calculated.




Keyboard commands:
[S]: Saves a PNG image of 4000x4000 pixels without glow filter
[SHIFT + S]: Saves a 4000x4000 pixel PNG image and applies a glow filter (may take a long time depending on your system)

URL parameters:
Add the parameter size=N to generate an image of NxN pixels (glow effect will be disabled by default)
Add the parameter glow=true to apply a glow effect to the image




Artist: Estienne
July 2022

metadata.name: Symbology437 #17
metadata.description:
Abstract, distorted compositions using symbols from the original IBM VGA codepage 437 character set. The symbols were created in code as bitmaps, scaled, and then drawn onto the canvas. The shading is based on the characters and sets from ANSI and ASCII art styles. 

There are 4 main types of outputs:
- Abstracts, 50%
- Random characters, 25%
- One of 16 preset character layouts, 25%
- One of 16 custom symbol PFP styles that will be 10% of the total outputs

For abstracts, there are several main styles created from layering different base shapes: circles, filled circles, rectangles, flow field lines, and rain-like streaks.

Color combinations include monochromatic, green or amber, dark mode, and multicolor.

Press 's' to save the image. The size is 2318x3000px, and for PFPs, the size is 3000x3000px.

metadata.name: Departure Within Shattered Windmills #15
metadata.description:
I wrote the following when reviewing the outputs...

The wind is gone,
My windmill falls,
I reach out to catch the pieces.
Half fall in my right hand,
The others in my left,
Two stacks of colored paper.
Iâ€™m holding my windmill,
I feel the breeze in my hair.
Each hand is empty,
My windmill rises,
I can see the wind.

'Departure Within Shattered Windmills' was originally inspired by suprematism, and then started to gain more complexity. It is still a combination of simple features, subdivided quads drawn on different planes of perspective. Chaos simulated by many organized grids. Countless pieces of a windmill.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.
